The nursery school is also part of the offices that have included architects.
the administrative building Avriopoint of Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini nursery school with everything you need - color walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch. design employees can go there.
The Arch. Design. architectural project company, whose workshops produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini nursery school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, especially of the age of children, and it was important for women architects and project managers to be able to return to work quickly.
At the same time as reduced-time employment contracts, the nursery school is a bonus offered to its employees by Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
This allows builders and architects to combine work that takes care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design. themselves who imagined this nursery school and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the operational human resources programme and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
They were able to purchase equipment and equipment and after two years to provide qualified personnel and start-up.
After the use of the funding endowment (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini nursery school from its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and Economy rating helped to make the staffing request.
Children are cared for by qualified staff, a nurse and a nursery school teacher take care of the children all day long. Children can go to nursery school without age limits, but they are more than three years old for the most part.
As it is a "mini-school nursery" there can be only 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who replace themselves.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school without regard to the hierarchical position.
Although it takes on individual care and education, the curriculum of the mini-school is comparable to that of pre-school education.
Children are not only playing, but they are also taught quality - from the beginning to school preparation, English is taught.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their child and do not have the stress of a delay to pick up the children in a school away from the parents' workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that a natural relationship of loyalty is created between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.is thus listed among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and that are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens the marketing of HR.
The bone house fascinates again after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudi's interiors.
The toy resembles the back of a prehistoric saurien, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
Thus is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona of architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received from the premises the nickname of House in Bone.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, façade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudi.
The front façade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that recall nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation one sees geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
In the night the façade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brilliance of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measurement.
The wood copies in waves windows frames, balustrades, decorative elements of doors, oeilleton and slats.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house ended in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a rich entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-dwelling house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations were born for an apartment of representation of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
For the façade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for Casa Battlo's plans began with successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila's house and Guell Park in which there are other Gaudi's works.
The premises nicknamed the hot house just after its finish because of its organic forms "the Bone House".
Others, having regard to the specific mechanism of window opening, called it "the house that stutters".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint Georges the patron of Catalonia.
Other elements of construction sculpture contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its time of central heating, with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the construction guidelines then and did not allow himself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained a building permit from the city, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finish the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
For example, members of the municipal council were not pleased that the pillars of construction impounded on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city's call Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a shared living room and on the third there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jeweller.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one access to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and the high society can communicate comfortably or restrict itself to private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has received in addition to new facades a non-traditional toaster and two more floors.
Gaudi's game with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which is decorated the inner courtyard and with the skylights.
The two-colour game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that the white reflects more than the dark which on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
Casa Battlo, which was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a lucrative business and extended the scope of the visits to common areas and the attic including the roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discounts.
The sum is still above the entrance price to Gaudi's other constructions in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
