Special ammunition of 25 mm calibre developed for this rifle and containing a highly breaking explosive, actually works as small grenades.
Ammunition can be programmed in such a way that it will explode in contact with the target but also at any point in their ballistic trajectory.
It can therefore be used against an enemy who hides behind an obstacle, a wall or a ditch.
He is also not protected from above and when he falls on a deadly rain of steel bursts, it can put him out of combat too.
According to Richard Audette who took part in the development of the XM-25, the new rifle is the first infantry weapon to use "intelligent" technology.
"The soldier uses it essentially in such a way that he finds the target, sends him a laser beam that determines the distance, thus obtains a precise point of view, according to which he corrects his sighting site and presses on the relaxation.
"Let's say you shot at 543 meters."
"When you press the trigger, the weapon loads and pulls at a distance of 543 meters more or less 1, 2, 3 meters," said Audette.
400 off-site jobs
Fujitsu Group relocates its subsidiary from Bad Homburg to Frankfurt.
Next year in July, 400 employees will transfer to Astro Park their place of work, which is currently located in the office building of Mareinbader Square in the Bad Homburg area.
The Japanese group Fujitsu relocates its branch from Bad Homburg to Frankfurt.
As the computer manufacturing and maintenance giant said on Wednesday, next year in July, the 400 men's and women's workplace, located so far on the Marienbader Square of the city of Bad Homburg, will be transferred to Astro Park, a huge office complex located on Lyoner Straße Street in the Niederrad district of Frankfurt.
A spokesman for Fujitsu explained that in the medium term, the group is expected to pool 100 other jobs that have been scattered so far in the region.
The rental offer has been extremely attractive. Moreover, the Astro Park open area offices are better suited to the way employees work.
Also in Bad Homburg, Fujitsu was just a tenant.
Managing Director Bernd Wagner said: "Frankfurt-Niederrad is a prime location with a remarkable infrastructure for us."
He claims that connection to the airport is of great importance to a global company like Fujitsu.
The new move of a major company inside the region yesterday sparked the joy of the winners and caused the disappointment of the losers.
The head of economic affairs of the municipality of Frankfurt, Mr Markus Frank (CDU), said that once again a "global actor" had been conquered.
It is a "extraordinary profession of faith relative to the place of establishment".
Fujitsu is suitable for the city and its establishment is an important impetus for Niederrad.
The mayor of Bad Homburg, Michael Korwisi (the Greens), regrets Fujitsu's decision.
Management informed the municipality of this intention at an early stage.
"It goes without saying that we have offered our assistance to this company," said Mr Korwisi.
However, friendly relations could not have changed the difficulties of the computer manufacturer vis-à-vis the owner of the Marienbader Square building.
In the end, economic reasons would have been decisive.
It is now a matter of preventing such an exceptional place from remaining unoccupied for a long time.
"I hope the owner and lessor of the building will be cooperative."
Ten years ago, the building of Place de l'Hôtel de Ville, used so far by Fujitsu and the nearby "small vertical", as well as the rest of the buildings of Place Marienbad, were part of the controversial construction project of the spa.
As a result of a joint project between the municipality and a private project developer, a new entrance to the city was created between the railway station and the City Hall. This was a source of criticism, not only because of the impressive layout of the areas that used to be used partly as parking space, but also because of the height of the buildings.
In 2001, the rating and investment consulting company, Feri, the computer manufacturer for travel distribution systems, Start Amadeus, as well as Fujitsu, the computer manufacturer at the time still associated with Siemens, moved into the buildings.
In 2006, the German group of Immobilien-Chancen specialized Frankfurt bought the buildings occupied by Fujitsu together with the Morgan Stanley real estate fund. A year later, these buildings were sold to the Spanish company Falcon Real Estate Investments SA based in Madrid.
The Fujitsu group based in Tokyo is considered the third largest provider of IT products in the world.
For example, it makes computers and servers available to businesses and also provides the essential service.
Its branch in the Rhine-Main region is one of the largest in Germany: Fujitsu certainly has many more employees in Munich.
The branch, Fujitsu Technology Solutions, leaves Bad Homburg to move to Frankfurt-Niederrad. The other subsidiaries present on this site are Fujitsu Services and a company named TDS.
For this, 7,000 square meters have been rented in the Astro Park building.
This 20-year-old complex, whose name recalls its star-shaped plan, houses among other things the headquarters of the Confederation of the Electronics and Electrotechnical Industry.
