The University of Ice
At the "Gelato University" in Bologna, ice confectioners are prepared for the best seasons of the year.
The three-day introductory course for future glaciers was very successful and attracted visitors from all over the world.
By the way, where does all the ice come from?
Glacier and ice machine.
The glacier, in German the somewhat old-fashioned ice confectioner, manufactures cream according to all the rules of Italian ice making art.
The ice turbine removes the ice cream from the refrigerated window with a spatula, disposes it in the waffle and then starts selling it.
To find out, there is no need to go to Anzola dell'Emilia in the province of Bologna.
But anyone who wants to know more about the ice can't avoid "Gelato-University" of the Italian firm Carpigiani.
The manufacturer of sorbetières founded the University of Ice in 2003 to ensure that ice creams released from its machines meet all the high Italian ideals.
The three-day introductory course for future glaciers was very successful and attracted visitors from all over the world.
Special courses are also offered on chocolate ice cream over several days. Practical sessions are also organized in the private ice cream shop.
In the middle of the mid-life crisis, a number of people dream of a new career, others simply risk to fulfill their ardent desire on smooth ice.
This time, 40 participants came from 19 countries from all continents, from Brazil to Saudi Arabia and Hungary.
Jacky, a professor of art education from California, is passionate about Slow Food. He wants to offer a quality European product in the future in the country of Industrial Ice.
Anke from Berlin is an advisor in business management and after a few years she wants to get something unique out of this challenging job for her nerves.
Two young Egyptians dream of opening a ice cream shop in Cairo.
A man from Malta and another from Brazil would like to improve the quality of ice cream in their bars, and the Canadian maid came because her children love Italian ice cream.
The master glacier Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal characteristics of perfect ice.
Is decisive not only the right flavor, but also the silky flexibility and consistency.
However, Luciano does not forget during the formation the cherry on the cake of the national superstructure and, in general, from the south: "The Italian ice cream is simply the best: and then it still retains a sacred dose of romanticism."
The first step in manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano pours the basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer that heats everything to 85 degrees thanks to an electronic program, then immediately cools to four degrees.
It then opens a tap installed on the machine: a white cream of pasteurized base, the foundation of all kinds of milk ice cream.
The trainer is immediately assailed by the question: Is it possible to make ice using only natural substances without stabilizer?
How can the personal pleasure of experimentation be given free rein?
Mr Luciano warns against being misled by the spirit of time.
Those who speak only of ice cream "made from natural ingredients" may, however, have used stabilizers: most often a natural product, e.g. guar seed flour obtained from guar bean.
It is obviously possible to make ice without using stabilizers, only it has to be sold within 24 hours, otherwise it collapses and the customer will croak nothing but ice pellets.
Some changes in the basic mass are permitted.
This becomes more exciting with aromas.
Master Luciano makes the difference between the ingredients that are purchased in the fruit or confectionery department of the supermarket.
In addition, there is powder and pasta.
"The suppliers will all try to feed you dozens of flavoured ingredients."
"However, you should just try."
Either in fruit sorbets recipes with sugar and fresh fruit.
Either in ice cream made from the white base mass which, by adding eggs to it, becomes a yellow cream and, when added cocoa powder, constitutes the basis of all possible chocolate desserts.
Now, all participants in the course must move on to the use of ice machines.
Luciano invites them from time to time to make four kinds of ice cream: vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut with or without eggs in the base mass, with more or less vanilla aroma or other natural ingredients.
The different kinds of fruit ice creams are also subject to the same experience.
More aromatic substances, more fruit purées: from the point of view of taste, this is not absolutely better.
Hazelnut ice does not necessarily have the taste of the nut, when it consists largely of hazelnuts.
The very popular kiwi ice is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizer.
"Only a well-balanced mixture correctly reflects the taste of ice," says Luciano.
Ice making is a calculation exercise: if fishing puree is used with a lot of sugar, the amount of sugar must be reduced in the basic recipe.
A sugar supplement is required for lemon ice cream.
Luciano presents an apparatus with which he determines the sugar content of the different types of fruit (the winemakers use it to measure the degree of Oechsle in grape must).
Fortunately, the tables make the calculations easier.
The manufacture of ice no longer requires as much physical intervention as before.
It is not only the machine for the automatic manufacture of the basic mass that helps.
There is also a device in which the available ice mixture is simultaneously beaten to make it unctuous and reduced to negative temperatures.
Despite all automations, slight failures are not excluded.
The Brazilian Gustavo buffs himself with fruit purée from head to toe and, thus, splashes his fellow students when the control of the colossal mixing bowl escapes him.
Master Luciano is of the opinion that an "incident like this could happen during each course: it is only a matter of time."
Controllers in an ambiguous position
According to some sources, the industry that is experimenting with the cultivation of genetically modified plants has established the European Food Safety Authority.
This accusation is now made by the Testbiotech Panel, which is considered an independent institute for assessing the consequences of biotechnology.
"It sounds like a conspiracy theory, but we are well informed," said Christoph Then, Director of Testbiotech, in Munich on Wednesday.
There is some information that the chairman of the Efsa Expert Group on Genetically Modified Plants, Mr Harry Kuiper, and other Efsa experts are under contract with the Ilsi Pressure Group.
The latter is funded by groups such as Monsanto, Nestlé or Bayer.
Mr. Kuiper has been instrumental in developing the Efsa test requirements for genetically modified plants and is therefore clearly in a conflict of interest situation, according to the criticisms expressed by Mr. Then.
The requirements drawn up correspond, by sub-paragraphs, to the positions taken by the Ilsi pressure group and thus bear the mark of the industry which would basically be controlled by the authorities installed in Parma in Italy.
This is already the second time that Testbiotech has denounced a conflict of interest.
A senior Efsa official has recently joined the Swiss food group Syngenta unconditionally or without a transitional period. In doing so, it has changed sides.
Not long ago, even the Central German Radio (Mitteldeutsche Rundfunk, MDR) had revealed the existence of personal relations between the European Union supervisory authority and the industrial lobby, which aroused suspicions from both the German Federal Environment Agency and MEPs.
However, Efsa does not admit the existence of any conflict of interest.
An opinion was expressed that all reliable data, including industry data, are being used as long as they are of good professional quality.
Experts working on behalf of Efsa are not prohibited from making contact with this sector of activity.
But they should make them public.
Mr. Kuiper admits that he works for the International Life Sciences Institute (ILSI) based in the United States.
This organization sees itself as a neutral forum bringing together experts from science, industry and policy, among others, to assess the risks of biotechnology without being in the balance of a lobby.
In this case, independent experts such as Mr. Then disagree that genetically modified plants are accepted without any animal feeding tests and that the impact of these plants on the environment has not been tested.
"We want to know what, for example, the impact of genetically modified maize causes in the field," says Mr. Then.
The current practice is to test only isolated proteins and not the entire genetically modified plant, which does not provide reliable results.
"If we don't look for the risks, how can we then discover them?" asks Mr. Then in an accusatory tone.
That is also Mrs Angelika Hilbeck's point of view.
This scientist has been researching genetics since 1994 and is currently working at the Zurich Polytechnic.
In this region, as in the United States, and now also in Europe, the industry sector is increasingly trying to influence or discredit critical scientists.
For this reason, there are still hardly any researchers who are not related to companies.
In the view of companies, critical studies would not be published.
Ms Hilbeck states that "industry controls safety research".
