Ogoni country is dry
The water flowing through the rivers is oiled brown; it smells like that in the gas station: Due to a leak, billions of litres of crude oil have destroyed the Ogoni country in Nigeria.
Men live on theft, corruption and oil refining.
Celestine Akpobari has a good intention.
"Don't wear yourself out," said the environmental activist to journalists to calm them down: "You still have enough oil mud in front of the water lens today."
The 37-year-old Nigerian tried to photograph a young man in the mud water to the chest, as well as the greasy trail around him: This scene seems almost beautiful in the brightness of water in the color of the rainbow.
It cannot be seen that the basement is full of brown tablescloths of crude oil.
On the bank of the Bodo-Jetty River, Esther Badom tells us that she used to collect shrimp in whole buckets here.
But in the meantime the calm waters have completely tarnished.
Five years ago, a huge amount of oil came out of an oil pipeline that exploded in the huge swamp.
Fishermen living in the neighbouring small town of Bodo must now row for six hours to reach the fishy waters: The Ogoni country in the heart of the Niger Delta is considered one of the most polluted regions in the world.
The full extent of the ravages is evident when the mangrove marshes crossed by streams are traversed.
Instead of clear water, the motor boat splits a crading brown water. Anyone who dips his hand in it removes it all covered with oil.
The roots of mangrove pups emerge from the soil like licorice sticks. Isolated palms sadly leave their palms hanging.
We seek in vain the clouds of birds, as we usually encounter in the wetlands: As soon as the outboard engine stops, a ghostly silence falls on this paradise of the past that looks like a gas station by the smell it emits.
"What is happening here is war on the environment," says Celestine Akpobari in a sad air: "Our life is characterized by a permanent danger to health."
The comparison of wars is made.
