The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the related case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of Real Madrid's entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which in past occasions sentenced its players to a fine for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to its dilated history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of conduct not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether with these actions one commits a fraud by law; for, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulations, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to look at the type of harm they cause to the sport spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in danger, that is, there has been no violent game.
Another of these assets that are alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the team of infractors from profiting in an unfair way from the contrary team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not accommodate itself to what is normally characterized as cheating o fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalization of the referee.
They were waiting and willing to accept the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that the infractors obtain from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a position of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action assumes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
Of course the advantage is that the players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without any boxes that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of inetermination, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and switch to the second cycle of cartons, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing the ladders, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which is still part of strategic decision-making that favours the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not operate to avoid the application of the sanction (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they chose rather the moment in which they submitted themselves to it.
They made a strategic decision without thwarting the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and law fraud is diffused, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, appears because of two factors: for there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director was transmitted to provoke them.
The evil caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
