Hackers vengeful and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals itself as an apparent scandal, a scandal which appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and prefigures a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file made up of a secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those of which Berlusconi owns), and Khadafi's sinister caricature profile has long been for cabaret artists to sketch.
The rule that secret records should be composed only of new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous books.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do new research (and does not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and reconfirm what they had already learned.
It's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (if not it could be, what do I know, editor of Liberation), who holds as true only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
Then why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can call themselves or take a plane to meet at dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some small performance exercises, have turned into spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place American diplomacy in the wrong light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put the victims in so much crisis as the "bourreaux".
But come to the deep nature of what has happened.
Once, in Orwell's time, we could conceive of any power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway travelled and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we show, as happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the opportunity to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret of secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to remove all power from him.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury to a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on-line any reserved information - it would be like publishing it on a poster stuck at the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, there is no hope of being able to maintain confidential contact over the telephone.
Nothing easier than to find out if and when a Head of State travelled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved reports be maintained in the future?
I know very well that for the moment, my forecast is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in uncontrollable stages, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at the most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: in the background, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that the technology is now moving in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wire telegraph (telephones).
The videocassettes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and back and discovering all the secrets of the editing, while now the CDs (digitals) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that communications policy and techniques go back to horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of embassies.
Now it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: how France steals its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the rapidly released (fast start or early) financing promises made by developed countries.
And the big French tweaks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (or €420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU released the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency process is valuable and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
In 2010, the EU announced that it had committed €2.2 billion, putting it on the right track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being to the detriment of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained, adding 150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France believes that the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, France's total support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to meet its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each chooses its method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ lent is equivalent to 1€ given.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain profitable investments (often projects related to mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a given euro... At most, it should be counted as part of its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has no reason to do so: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% of loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1€ to satisfy its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
That's a nice trick.
To sum up, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, it can lead to the impression that it is spending 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy did the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it was enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term question in relation to all the climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
In any event, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could move forward the discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
