A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published this Wednesday by Generations Futures (ex-Movement for Rights and Respect for Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with", bought between July and September foods usually consumed in four meals and one snack in one day by a child of ten years old, in supermarkets of the Oise and Paris.
These standard meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as treats, were examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is overwhelming: 81 chemical substances, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each individual chemical are not exceeded, it is clear from our survey that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern," notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three known as certain carcinogens as well as nearly 20 residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, shows traces of six chemical substances, one of which is banned in France.
The same applies to Kenya's green beans, included in lunch, on which the study found traces of a strong insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, minced steak, canned tuna, and even the baguette and chewing gum were filled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroforms.
For dinner, salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the microwave meal was not exempt.
The final consumer risk of this "contaminant cocktails" is "probably underestimated", according to the study.
The Europe Ecology-Greens Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
